12
00:01:05,793 --> 00:01:07,764
Answer crisply and move on.

13
00:01:07,764 --> 00:01:11,129
Q: What is FastAPI and why is it fast?

14
00:01:11,129 --> 00:01:16,346
A modern Python web framework built on Starlette (ASGI) and Pydantic.

15
00:01:16,346 --> 00:01:27,956
It's fast for two reasons: it's async-native (ASGI lets it handle many concurrent I/O-bound requests without blocking), and Pydantic does validation in highly optimized code.

16
00:01:27,956 --> 00:01:34,182
The third "fast" is developer speed — automatic OpenAPI docs and type-based validation.

17
00:01:34,182 --> 00:01:38,293
Q: How does FastAPI generate API docs automatically?

18
00:01:38,293 --> 00:01:48,293
From your type hints and Pydantic models, it builds an OpenAPI schema, served as interactive Swagger UI (/docs) and ReDoc (/redoc).

19
00:01:48,293 --> 00:01:53,545
The same type hints drive validation and documentation — define once, get both.

20
00:01:53,545 --> 00:01:56,538
Q: What's a Pydantic model and why use one?

21
00:01:56,538 --> 00:01:59,387
A class that declares the shape and types of data.

22
00:01:59,387 --> 00:02:05,036
FastAPI uses it to validate and parse request bodies and serialize responses.

23
00:02:05,036 --> 00:02:12,776
Invalid input is rejected with a structured 422 before your handler runs — you never hand-write validation boilerplate.

24
00:02:12,776 --> 00:02:17,572
Moving on to Level 2: The async model (where most candidates stumble).

25
00:02:17,572 --> 00:02:22,656
This is the single most important area, and the most common place people get exposed.

26
00:02:22,656 --> 00:02:26,610
Q: What's the difference between def and async def for a route?

27
00:02:26,610 --> 00:02:28,665
This is the FastAPI gotcha.

28
00:02:28,665 --> 00:02:36,502
A route defined with async def runs on the event loop — great for await-ing I/O (DB, HTTP calls).

29
00:02:36,502 --> 00:02:41,286
A route defined with plain def is run in a threadpool so it doesn't block the loop.

30
00:02:41,286 --> 00:02:42,115
The trap:

31
00:02:42,115 --> 00:02:54,014
If you write async def and then call a blocking function inside it (a synchronous DB driver, time.sleep, requests.get), you block the entire event loop — every concurrent request stalls.

32
00:02:54,014 --> 00:02:59,314
Strong answer: "Use async def only when everything inside is awaitable.

33
00:02:59,314 --> 00:03:08,329
If I must call a blocking library, either use a sync def route (FastAPI threadpools it) or push the work off the loop with run_in_executor."

34
00:03:08,329 --> 00:03:11,406
Saying this out loud signals real experience.

35
00:03:11,406 --> 00:03:16,502
Q: How do you run a blocking/CPU-bound task without killing throughput?

36
00:03:16,502 --> 00:03:35,817
Three options, by case: a plain def route (auto-threadpooled), await loop.run_in_executor(...) for a blocking call inside an async route, or — for genuinely heavy CPU work — offload to a background worker (Celery, Dramatiq, or an external queue) rather than doing it in the request at all.

37
00:03:35,817 --> 00:03:39,362
Next up: Level 3: Dependency injection.

38
00:03:39,362 --> 00:03:44,399
DI is FastAPI's signature feature and a favourite interview topic.

39
00:03:44,399 --> 00:03:47,307
Q: How does FastAPI's Depends work?

40
00:03:47,307 --> 00:03:53,569
You declare a dependency as a function; FastAPI calls it and injects its result into your handler.

41
00:03:53,569 --> 00:04:00,661
Dependencies can have their own dependencies (a tree), are resolved per-request, and are cached within a request.

42
00:04:00,661 --> 00:04:05,216
It's how you wire DB sessions, auth, and shared config cleanly.

43
00:04:05,216 --> 00:04:07,560
Q: Why use yield in a dependency?

44
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:16,153
Code before yield runs on the way in (acquire a DB session); code after yield runs on the way out (close it) — even if the handler raised.

45
00:04:16,153 --> 00:04:26,634
It's FastAPI's clean equivalent of setup/teardown, perfect for resource lifecycle like DB connections — which ties straight into connection pooling.

46
00:04:26,666 --> 00:04:31,796
Let's explore Level 4: Production depth (the mid-level differentiators).

47
00:04:31,796 --> 00:04:34,825
These follow-ups are where the mid-level offer is won.

48
00:04:34,825 --> 00:04:40,053
They're rarely about FastAPI syntax and mostly about whether you've operated a service.

49
00:04:40,053 --> 00:04:43,515
Q: A FastAPI endpoint is slow under load.

50
00:04:43,515 --> 00:04:44,572
How do you debug it?

51
00:04:44,572 --> 00:04:56,700
Walk the layers out loud: confirm with p95/p99 metrics (not averages); check whether a blocking call is stalling the event loop; inspect the database (slow query?

52
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:57,878
pool exhausted?

53
00:04:57,878 --> 00:05:05,438
— see connection pooling); look for an N+1 query; check whether a cache stampede hits the DB at TTL boundaries.

54
00:05:05,438 --> 00:05:08,971
Structured reasoning beats a single guessed answer.

55
00:05:08,971 --> 00:05:13,647
Q: How do you handle background work — say, sending an email after signup?

56
00:05:13,647 --> 00:05:20,137
For light, fire-and-forget work, FastAPI's BackgroundTasks runs it after the response is sent.

57
00:05:20,137 --> 00:05:30,894
For anything that can fail, retry, or is heavy, use a real task queue (Celery/Dramatiq) so the work is durable and the web process stays responsive.

58
00:05:30,894 --> 00:05:35,185
Knowing when BackgroundTasks is not enough is the senior signal.

59
00:05:35,185 --> 00:05:37,733
Q: How do you make a POST safe to retry?

60
00:05:37,733 --> 00:05:45,834
Idempotency keys — accept a client-generated key, claim it atomically, replay the stored result on duplicates.

61
00:05:45,834 --> 00:05:54,212
This is a great moment to reference real experience; I wrote it up in idempotency keys: how we stopped double-charging customers.

62
00:05:54,212 --> 00:05:57,902
Q: How do you structure a large FastAPI project?

63
00:05:57,902 --> 00:06:10,606
Routers per domain (APIRouter), a settings module (Pydantic BaseSettings), dependencies for DB/auth, a service layer separating business logic from HTTP, and Alembic for migrations.

64
00:06:10,606 --> 00:06:16,039
Emphasize separation of concerns — handlers thin, logic in services.

65
00:06:16,039 --> 00:06:23,767
Q: Sync framework (Django/Flask) vs FastAPI — when would you not pick FastAPI?

66
00:06:23,767 --> 00:06:25,089
Maturity signal.

67
00:06:25,089 --> 00:06:30,774
FastAPI shines for async, I/O-bound, API-first services.

68
00:06:30,774 --> 00:06:39,103
Django still wins when you want batteries-included (admin, ORM, auth) and a large team moving fast on a CRUD-heavy product.

69
00:06:39,103 --> 00:06:45,353
The honest "it depends" with reasons beats fanboying — expanded in FastAPI vs Django.

70
00:06:45,353 --> 00:06:47,325
